@sipa what would you static assert on? When you declare the std_array type, you need to specify the length of the array, and the array is always going to be that size. eg this compiles:

```
enum class en {
    thing1,
    thing2,
    thing3,  // added a new thing
    MAX,
};

int main()
{
    std::array<std::string, (int)en::MAX> a {"thing1 description", "thing2 description"}; // oops, didn't add a thing3 description. a[2] is default initialized to empty string
    static_assert(a.size() == (int)en::MAX); // always passes
    for (const auto& x : a) {
        std::cout << x << std::endl;
    }
}
```

Would you replace the value in the static_assert with a hard-coded value?

